social_posts.post_text: Going to party like it’s 2014. ✨

The good and the bad. I had a fun weekend with friends, food and a *few* drinks. For a couple days, I just lived like I used to live and I needed that. I think the absolutely hideous smile a slide over will show you how much fun I was having. 

Simultaneously, I’ve spent the last few days in a lot of pain. My sentinel node biopsy probably damaged some nerves. It feels like I got kicked in the ribs and I sometimes go numb on my entire left side. I also have major scar tissue under both incisions (thanks body) but heat and massaging is helping (so I’ve spent my entire week working while simultaneously massaging my boob, so if you work with me and my Teams camera was off that may have been why). 

This is a big week. I have a lot on my mind. Today I should find out more about my radiation plan, and I expect to receive my surgery pathology results on Friday. 

I’m doing my best to stay busy and not think of the worst case scenario, that all sentinel nodes are positive for cancer despite chemo. It’s hard not to go there sometimes, but I am doing my best to manifest *no evidence of disease.*

Wish me luck. 

🤞🏼❤️
All I really know lately is that every day is a gift. Enjoy it. 🥂
Warm is the aesthetic. ⛄️ #ootd

A little bit of life lately. 

Trying to be a little like the old me - well manicured and in a good outfit - but these past few days have also been challenging. My anxiety was very high end of last week and into this week. I wasn’t sleeping very well.

The reality of cancer is that there aren’t many certainties. Having done neo-adjuvant chemotherapy and still having positive lymph nodes is apparently a bit of a medical grey area. I have never liked grey areas. I didn’t know if this meant I would need to remove more or all lymph nodes in the area.

After speaking with my oncologist yesterday, she feels confident that remaining cancer is microscopic and can be treated with radiation and endocrine therapy. Further surgery is not needed at this time. I’m considered to be on the other side of this. I was, of course, happy to hear this news. And yet, I still feel in a kind of limbo. There are probably still cancer cells in me, we’re betting on radiation working and hormone therapy keeping them from growing, but they might still be there. That’s the thing about cancer, you never know if or when it’s going to come back with a vengeance.

“Survivorship” is this weird place of mixed emotions. You’re happy, you’re scared, you’re hopeful and you’re anxious. It’s living with this all of the time. Your hair is also crazy. 

For now the path forward is 21-28 days of radiation (had my mapping and freckle tattoos done this week), aromatase inhibitors for the next several years, continuing with my goserelin injections monthly, eventual zoledronic acid infusions, and waiting to see if I qualify for abemaciclib. All of this mixed with annual screening, ultrasounds and scans to keep an eye on things. 

I always thought you got rid of cancer and that was that, but that’s not how it works. Surviving cancer is more like living while actively preventing cancer. So, cheers to life as a “survivor.” I’m happy to be here, but it’s a really, really weird place. If we are out for a night of fun, please remind me to take my pills. #breastcancerawareness #breastcancersurvivor #breastcancerunder35

Trigger warning: drain & blood on 3rd slide. 

This will be me for the next little while. Bundled with a glazed face. 

For those that are new here, I was diagnosed with breast cancer in June 2022. Unfortunately, we learned through a sentinel node biopsy that after neo-adjuvant chemotherapy, despite some shrinkage, I still had macro-metastasis in 2 of the 4 nodes taken. The third node had isolated tumor cells. It was decided that an axillary node dissection was needed to ensure cancer was not left behind. My cancer was clearly chemotherapy resistant, and anything left behind would likely be even more resistant now. I’m hoping with all my might that most of what they took is negative for cancer, for extra peace of mind. 

So for now, I have a fun (gross) drain attached to my body. It’s thankfully not bothering me as much as I thought it would.

Tomorrow I will have my bandages removed and be able to shower (life’s little joys these days). My drain will come out in two weeks or maybe sooner if the drainage is limited for two days in a row.

Let me be your reminder to trust yourself. If your body is telling you something, listen to it and always advocate for yourself. 🫶🏼 #breastcancerawareness #breastcancerunder35 #breastcancersurvivor
At least cancer lets you try a lot of new hair styles. Won’t call it a silver lining though. #bangs #wiglife

Life hasn’t been so sweet for me for the last 9 months, but today has been the closest thing. So incredibly thankful that none of the nodes taken during my axillary dissection were positive for malignancy. I can sleep a little easier knowing that we probably got all of the damn thing. I’m still in a lot of pain, and have radiation to complete (and years of endocrine therapy and pills) but today we celebrate a win. The future is never certain, but I’m throwing everything I have at this. Love you all and thank you for supporting me. #breastcancersurvivor #breastcancerunder35

Today I really miss travelling. I haven’t been able to do much since diagnosis, at the liberty of a million appointments. Of course my health matters most, but it’s been incredibly challenging to feel like I’m missing out on living, while everyone else my age seems to be having the time of their lives. I am hoping that can change this year, and I can get back a little piece of my former identity. Get back to living, not just surviving. Until then, here’s one of my favourite old pictures.🤞🏼

I’ve learned a few things over the past year: never devote yourself fully to something that can’t devote itself to you. A great career is worthwhile, but will never love you back. Know your worth. Life is short, spend it wisely. People matter most (and dogs are angels on earth).

💓

I’m not really sure how to be this short hair person, but I’m going to do it.

My reality is that cold capping worked, I never went bald. I kept a lot of hair until the very end, but it came out in clumps after chemotherapy finished. I basically just had a mullet at the back and nothing but regrowth at the front. I hated looking in the mirror. I couldn’t do it anymore. So I cut all the long pieces off.

We’ll fix this up. Add some highlights to mask the greys, and learn to love it. #itsnotjusthair #breastcancerunder35 #breastcancer

Back in a place that brings me mixed emotions. Happy to still be here, sad for what I’ve been forced to endure, anxious but energized to make a difference. What most people misunderstand about a cancer diagnosis is that so much continues to happen after active treatment to prevent recurrence. 

Given that cancer has a higher risk of recurrence in younger people (the most simple reason is that we just have more years for it to happen in), you throw a lot at it. Today is my first Zometa infusion. This is the *final* medication being layered in to prevent recurrence and to add calcium back to my bones.

Zometa (medical name zoledronic acid) adds calcium from my blood into my bones. This helps strengthen them as my endocrine therapy (Zoladex and Anastrozole) block estrogen production. The loss of estrogen causes bone density loss, which can lead to osteopenia and/or eventual osteoporosis. 

Simultaneously, it will also strengthen the bones in such a way that prevents tumours from being able to form in them. This makes bone metastasis more difficult. The bones are one of the most common places breast cancer would cause a secondary cancer. If this were to happen, I would have a Stage 4 breast cancer that would now be incurable. I am higher risk for the development of a Stage 4 breast cancer because I had lymph node metastasis at diagnosis, and still had lymph node metastasis after neoadjuvant chemotherapy. Thankfully most nodes were negative but in theory the cancer can be hiding elsewhere. It entered the river that leads to the ocean of my body. We don’t know what the future holds, but my oncologist believes in the power of Zometa to give the best chance of this not happening.

I will have 8 Zometa infusions, every 12 weeks for about 2 years. Side effects will likely be aches and flu like symptoms for a couple days. Maybe I will be lucky and avoid them, but I was warned to prepare to feel pretty rough for a few days.

So this is it, life as a cancer survivor. Unfortunately it’s never back to “business-as-usual.” There’s still lots going on behind the scenes. That’s what we all wish you knew - so I’m sharing it. #zometa #breastcancersurvivor #breastcancerunder35

Making time to #feelitonthefirst before some lunch time pilates. No matter what anyone tries to tell you (including government health agencies), self-assessment saves lives. I’m proof of this. Yes, finding a lump is anxiety inducing, and most are benign, but missing something that isn’t, is worse. Get to know your normal, and report any lump to your doctor. Pay attention to changes in your armpit and collarbone area, as well as any changes to your nipple and any discharge (sometimes you notice this before you can feel a lump). If you aren’t taken seriously, get another opinion. If you want imaging, you deserve imaging. Cancer doesn’t care how old you are, and remember that ultrasounds and/or MRI in addition to mammogram is best for dense breasts! #nottooyoung #breastcancerawareness #breastcancerunder35

June 2nd 2022, the day my life changed. 

One year ago I was told my biopsy was positive for invasive ductal carcinoma and that it had already metastasized to my lymph nodes. I took a picture crying that day, and then I decided to smile, put on a cute outfit and go to the Miranda Lambert concert. Cancer might take my life, but it wasn’t going to take the living. One year later, the hardest year later, I’m finally ready for so much more living. 

This past year has had very low, lows. By the end of chemo just looking in the mirror could bring me to tears. I looked and felt nothing like myself. Weight gain I couldn’t control, the complete loss of my eyebrows and eyelashes. Fists full of hair lost every time I showered despite cold capping. Exhausted. I was certain I would never look like myself again. 

By the time I finished my first surgery I felt like a shell of my former self and didn’t have any real desire to leave the house. Finding out I needed a second surgery, because chemo didn’t work as well as we had hoped and thought, shattered me. After my second surgery in January, I was so upset by the way my hair regrowth looked, I burst into tears and cut my hair myself. 

Radiation was like ground hog day, and the first month of Verzenio kicked my ass. 

Through it all, I had an amazing support system that ensured there were also days mixed in that I smiled, laughed and had some fun. 

I’m finally starting to feel more like myself, a new version. My perceptions of beauty have changed and I love my scars. I’m even starting to enjoy my short hair. 

A lot has happened in a year, but I’m just thankful I’m here.

Happy 1st #Cancerversary to me! 🎗️💓🫶🏼💫 #breastcancer #breastcancerawareness #breastcancersurvivor #breastcancerrebel

Raising awareness about breast cancer,  in particular in young women, is so important to me.

1 in 8 women* will be diagnosed with breast cancer in their lifetime. There is growing evidence that the number of young women being diagnosed with breast cancer is increasing. Outcomes for young women are worse because we are more likely to be diagnosed at a later stage, with lymph node positive disease, as I was. This is largely due to the reality that we are not eligible for routine screening in most cases, and identify our own cancers. Once in the lymphatic system cancer can return at a distant location. Distant metastasis is stage 4 breast cancer, and incurable. Being diagnosed later increases the likelihood this may happen.

The Canadian Cancer Society CIBC Run For The Cure has raised $493 million to fund breast cancer research projects since 1992. We have seen a 49% decrease in breast cancer mortality rates since the 1980s because of funding being directed to treatment for early stage breast cancer. But for me, Stage 4 still needs more. This is why I fundraise, for a future with a cure for all stages.

As a young survivor, I care immensely about improving outcomes for those with metastatic breast cancer. I am hopeful for a future with a cure for all stages of breast cancer, and for that reason I am again participating in the CIBC Run For The Cure in Kitchener-Waterloo on October 1st 2023. To date, I have raised over $2500 for my campaign which means I will be able to direct my donations specifically to metastatic breast cancer research! I invite you to join me and/or donate using the link in my bio!

#CIBCRunfortheCure #Stage4NeedsMore #CanadianCancerSociety @cancersociety @cibc @breastcancerccs #sponsored #ad 

*This statistic refers to those assigned female at birth, inclusive of transgender men and non-binary individuals.

One year later. This time last year I had no eyebrows (just some shading from the powder brows), no eye lashes, an incredibly puffy steroid face from having finished 8 rounds of dose dense chemotherapy, and an incredibly swollen boob and axilla. I was in agony, or high on hydromorphone and felt like shit about myself. I am so thankful to be where I am today. We don’t know what the future holds, but embracing every day. Heading into the last 3 days of year 33, and thankful I get to see year 34. 🫶🏼 #breastcancersurvivor #surgeryversary #lumpectomy #breastcancerunder35 #diagnosedat32

Well, I guess that about sums up my year: (extra) surgery & radiation, wearing wigs, finally cutting my hair while crying and then taking a selfie (how me), a few vacations (finally), amazing friends, weddings, new babies, lots of (absolutely brutal) cancer drugs and finally recognizing myself again (thank you hair extensions). 

2023, you were something. The first half was harder than I ever imagined. Adjusting to Zometa, Verzenio and ongoing radiation pains has been harder on me than I could have ever imagined. I thought I had the worst of it in 2022, I didn’t. In some ways chemotherapy was “easy” by comparison. 

April 2023 was the hardest month of my life. Plummeting neutrophils, nausea, vomiting, bowel issues like you can’t imagine, all while everyone thinks you’re “all better” (l-o-l). Verzenio literally almost killed me. But we figured it out, days are getting easier and easier. Anxiety still keeps me up at night sometimes but making this reminded me of a lot of amazing memories this year and that there’s a lot to look forward to.

I’m so happy to be starting 2024 with hair extensions. I’m so happy to be here. Cheers to another year of Verzenio, and more living, but please for the love of God, be easier on me this time.
